<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1834,2041]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1436,152,287]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="218" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1988" box="[151,365,1835,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Tergosmia">
<emphasis box="[151,224,1835,1861]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Osmia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[239,355,1835,1860]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Tergosmia</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
species are nonmetallic, robust and small to medium-sized bees (
<quantity box="[1086,1215,1834,1861]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.75" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" unit="mm" value="7.75" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="5.5">5.5–10 mm</quantity>
) with punctiform to short-linear parapsidal lines, a predominantly dull basal area of the propodeum and whitish to yellowish tergal hair bands, which are continuous or interrupted. Except for 
<taxonomicName authority="Benoist" authorityName="Benoist" box="[768,969,1906,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis box="[768,875,1906,1933]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">O. lunata</emphasis>
Benoist
</taxonomicName>
, the females are characterized by the lack of orange hairs or hair brushes along the apical margin of the clypeus, which are typical for most other Palaearctic representatives of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1806" box="[468,541,1979,2005]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,541,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Osmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The metasomal scopa is either whitish or blackish. Diagnostic characters of the males are the similar 
<taxonomicName box="[392,494,2014,2040]" form="and" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" rank="form">form and</taxonomicName>
size of sterna 2 and 3 lacking fringed emarginations and the strong median emargi- nation of sternum 5, which is beset with hairs except for 
<taxonomicName box="[792,899,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis box="[792,899,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="218">O. lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Male tergum 7 strongly varies in shape among species and is either prolonged into a long spine, narrowly rectangular with two lateral and widely spaced long teeth, bilobed or bispinose (
<figureCitation box="[394,521,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–23" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1446,1471]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1421]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,181,1421]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 15–23: Osmia (Tergosmia). 15: Female of O. tergestensis in front of her brood cell hidden in a rock fissure (photo A. Krebs). 16: Female of O. tergestensis folding petal after having it bitten off from flower of Geranium pyrenaicum (Geraniaceae; photo A. Krebs). 17: Brood cells of O. tergestensis between blades of dense grass tussock. 18: Brood cell of O. avosetta at the end of a short burrow in the ground (photo C. Sedivy). 19: Female of O. lunata depositing nectar in her brood cell built in a short burrow in the ground. 20–22: Male terga 6–7 of O. avosetta (20), O. lunata (21), O. rhodoensis (22) and O. tergestensis (23)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3826177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3826177/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="218">Fig. 20–23</figureCitation>
). As in most males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1806" box="[769,842,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[769,842,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="218">Osmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, tergum 6 lacks a lateral tooth except for 
<taxonomicName authority="Warncke" authorityName="Warncke" authorityYear="1988" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avosetta">
<emphasis box="[1309,1436,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="218">O. avosetta</emphasis>
Warncke
</taxonomicName>
and sternum 6 is devoid of membraneous basal flaps.
</paragraph>
